But can we appreciate the unconventional, uncomfortable feeling St. Chroma’s (as in the Tyler persona) entire existence gives, he’s dressed from the neck down on a suit and dress shoes, but is wearing a creepy smooth, uncanny valley mask. And the way he walks, oh my Earfquake the way he walks; it starts as a passionate, determined march accompanied with the powerful whispering; devolving into odd, boogeyman-like strides, adding to how unnerving it is. One day, you wake up and recognize the need for a new Tyler, The Creator album — not merely as music, but as a source of inspiration across multiple facets of life. His work defies predictability, offering profound insights even in tracks crafted for mainstream appeal. Tyler’s deliberate and often unconventional artistic choices not only enhance creative expression but also provoke deeper philosophical reflection. It’s inevitable that his oeuvre will soon be studied in academic contexts—spanning music theory, poetry, philosophy, contemporary art, visual identity, art direction, and cinematography.
